        <article class="prose">

          <!-- Recognition: empathy before proof -->
          <p>If you have spent years in treatment without a clear diagnosis, or been told "unexplained infertility" is an answer, you are not alone. Many patients arrive here after repeated cycles that never addressed the reason they could not conceive. This page presents the published, peer-reviewed evidence for Restorative Reproductive Medicine: 13 studies, more than 4,500 couples, data from 10 countries. The numbers speak for themselves.</p>

          <!-- Section 1: Key Takeaways -->
          <aside class="tldr">
            <h2 id="key-takeaways">Key Takeaways</h2>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>RRM research reports live birth rates ranging from 32% to 66% depending on patient population and follow-up duration.</strong> The largest published cohort of 1,310 couples reported an adjusted cumulative take-home baby rate of 62.1% at 36 months of follow-up.<sup><a href="#ref-1" id="cite-1">1</a></sup></li>
              <li><strong>RRM has been studied in over 4,500 couples across 10 countries on 4 continents.</strong> Published data spans the United States, Canada, the United Kingdom, Poland, Ireland, Spain, Italy, Germany, Australia, and Ukraine.</li>
              <li><strong>RRM achieves pregnancies even after failed IVF.</strong> In a cohort of 403 couples where 100% had prior IVF failure, RRM treatment produced a 32.1% adjusted cumulative live birth rate, with 92% of those babies born at full term.<sup><a href="#ref-9" id="cite-9">9</a></sup></li>
              <li><strong>RRM reduces "unexplained" infertility to under 10% of cases.</strong> One multicenter study found that comprehensive diagnostic evaluation lowered the proportion of idiopathic infertility from the typical 30 to 50% down to just 8%.<sup><a href="#ref-2" id="cite-2">2</a></sup></li>
              <li><strong>RRM births are overwhelmingly singleton and full-term.</strong> Published studies consistently report near-zero multiple pregnancy rates, a sharp contrast to the elevated twin and higher-order multiples associated with conventional fertility treatment.</li>
            </ul>
          </aside>

          <!-- Section 3a: Does RRM Work for Infertility? -->
          <h2 id="does-rrm-work">Does RRM Work for Infertility?</h2>

          <p>The short answer: yes, and the data are remarkably consistent across clinics, countries, and decades. The largest published RRM cohort followed 1,310 couples at a specialized clinic in Spain over five years. These were not easy cases. The median duration of infertility was 24 months, 27.5% had already attempted ART, and the mean number of diagnoses per couple was 2.5. The adjusted cumulative take-home baby rate was 62.1%.<sup><a href="#ref-1" id="cite-1a">1</a></sup> That means roughly six out of ten couples took home a baby after RRM treatment, with a median treatment duration of just 10.9 months.</p>

          <p>This result does not stand alone. In Ireland, Stanford and Boyle followed 1,072 couples treated with NaProTechnology in a general practice setting. The average female age was 35.8 years, couples had been trying for a mean of 5.6 years, and a third had previously attempted ART. The adjusted cumulative live birth rate at 24 months was 52.8%.<sup><a href="#ref-13" id="cite-13a">13</a></sup> In Canada, Tham reported on 108 couples (mean female age 35.4 years) and found an adjusted cumulative live birth rate of 66% at 24 months.<sup><a href="#ref-12" id="cite-12a">12</a></sup> In Australia, James studied 162 couples at a hospital-based multidisciplinary fertility clinic and reported an adjusted cumulative live birth rate of 57.4%.<sup><a href="#ref-6" id="cite-6a">6</a></sup> In Ukraine, Horodenchuk followed 282 couples and found an adjusted cumulative live birth rate of 73.6%.<sup><a href="#ref-7" id="cite-7a">7</a></sup></p>

          <p>The iNEST study brought this evidence to a new level. Designed as the first prospective, multicenter, international evaluation of RRM, iNEST enrolled 834 subfertile couples across 10 clinical sites in four countries (Canada, Poland, the UK, and the USA). Among all couples, 57% achieved at least one pregnancy and 44% achieved at least one live birth during the follow-up period.<sup><a href="#ref-4" id="cite-4a">4</a></sup> The mean number of diagnoses per couple was 4.7, with ovulation-related disorders in 87%, endometriosis in 31%, and abnormalities of semen analysis in 24%. These are real patients in real clinics, not a hand-picked research cohort.</p>

          <p>What makes this body of evidence compelling is not any single study. It is the pattern: different clinicians, different countries, different healthcare systems, different decades, and consistently strong outcomes. From Spain to Ukraine to Australia to Canada, RRM produces live birth rates that cluster between 50% and 70% when measured cumulatively over 24 months. The approach works because it asks a fundamentally different question: not "how do we bypass the problem?" but "what is the problem, and can we fix it?"</p>

          <!-- Section 3b: What if I've Already Tried IVF? -->
          <h2 id="after-ivf">What if I've Already Tried IVF?</h2>

          <p>This may be the question that matters most to the patients I see. If IVF did not work, does anything else stand a chance? The published data say yes. De Groot and Boyle studied 403 couples in Ireland where every single patient had already undergone IVF. These couples had averaged 2.1 IVF attempts (range 1 to 9), had been trying for 5.8 years, and only 5% had ever achieved a live birth from IVF. Their average age was 37.2. By every conventional measure, these were the most difficult cases. Despite those prognostic factors, the adjusted cumulative live birth rate with RRM was 32.1%. Among women aged 35 to 38, it was 37.5%. Even among women over 40, it was 27.4%.<sup><a href="#ref-9" id="cite-9a">9</a></sup> The average birth weight was 3,374 grams, 92% of babies were born at 37 or more weeks, and there were no very low birth weight babies.</p>

          <p>The Andrology study tells a complementary story. Among 1,014 couples evaluated with a comprehensive RRM protocol, 28.9% had previous ART failure (mean 2.3 cycles per couple). Even in that subgroup, the spontaneous pregnancy rate after targeted treatment was 36.1%.<sup><a href="#ref-2" id="cite-2a">2</a></sup> These pregnancies happened because the diagnostic workup uncovered treatable conditions that had never been identified or addressed during prior fertility treatment.</p>

          <p>This is the pattern I see in my own practice. A couple completes several IVF cycles, and no one has ever performed a thorough hormonal evaluation on a specific cycle day, checked for subclinical endometritis, treated a chronic male genital tract infection, or corrected a luteal phase defect. RRM does not succeed after IVF failure by being "better" at the same thing. It succeeds by asking different questions and treating the underlying causes that were never diagnosed.</p>

          <!-- Section 3c: Does Age Matter? -->
          <h2 id="age">Does Age Matter?</h2>

          <p>Yes, and I will be straightforward about what the data show. Age is a real biological factor, and no treatment, including RRM, erases its effects. The Sanchez-Mendez study provides the clearest age-stratified data: adjusted cumulative take-home baby rates were 83.7% for women aged 18 to 30, 53.3% for women 36 to 40, and 24.4% for women over 40.<sup><a href="#ref-1" id="cite-1b">1</a></sup> The Grande study reported approximately 50% pregnancy rates for women under 34 and approximately 30% for women under 40.<sup><a href="#ref-2" id="cite-2b">2</a></sup> De Groot and Boyle found that women 35 to 38 who had already failed IVF achieved a 37.5% live birth rate with RRM, while women over 40 reached 27.4%.<sup><a href="#ref-9" id="cite-9b">9</a></sup></p>

          <p>These numbers decline with age, as expected. But they also show that meaningful success is achievable well into the late thirties and, for some patients, into the forties. A 27.4% adjusted live birth rate for women over 40 who have already failed IVF is not a dismissal. It is a real chance.</p>

          <p>For patients worried about the clock, here is what I want you to know: the RRM diagnostic workup takes weeks, not years. A thorough evaluation, including cycle charting, targeted labs, ultrasound, and often a diagnostic laparoscopy, can typically be completed within two to three months. Treatment begins immediately as diagnoses are confirmed. You are not choosing between "doing something now" and "waiting." You are choosing between treatments that bypass the problem and treatments that solve it. The timeline difference is months, and the information gained from an RRM workup belongs to you regardless of what you decide to do next.</p>

          <!-- Section 3d: What About Male Factor Infertility? -->
          <h2 id="male-factor">What About Male Factor Infertility?</h2>

          <p>The man matters. In conventional fertility treatment, male factor infertility is often addressed with a single intervention: ICSI, which injects one sperm directly into an egg. The underlying cause of the abnormal semen parameters is rarely investigated. The Grande study in <em>Andrology</em> challenged this approach directly. Among 1,014 couples evaluated with a comprehensive multidisciplinary protocol, isolated male factor infertility was present in 23% of cases and combined male-female factors in another 45%. After thorough andrological evaluation, the proportion of idiopathic (unexplained) male infertility dropped from the typical 30 to 50% to just 8%.<sup><a href="#ref-2" id="cite-2c">2</a></sup></p>

          <p>What did they find? Among men with isolated male factor, genital tract inflammation was present in 48.8%, genital tract infection in 43.1%, and hypospermatogenesis in 16.7%. Normal semen parameters were observed in only 13% of this group. These are not obscure or untreatable conditions. Infections were treated with antibiotics and probiotics. Persistent inflammation was managed with low-dose corticosteroids and antioxidants. Hypospermatogenesis was treated with FSH. Varicocele was repaired surgically when severe. The overall spontaneous pregnancy rate across all treated couples was 40.9%.<sup><a href="#ref-2" id="cite-2d">2</a></sup></p>

          <p>RRM evaluates both partners because both partners contribute to fertility. When a man's infection is treated, his partner does not need ICSI. When inflammation resolves, sperm quality improves on its own. This is not a philosophical preference. It is a clinical strategy supported by a multicenter study of over one thousand couples.</p>

          <!-- Section 3e: How Long Does It Take? -->
          <h2 id="timeline">How Long Does It Take?</h2>

          <p>Time matters when you are trying to conceive, and I understand the urgency. The published data show that RRM pregnancies happen faster than many patients expect. In the Marshell study of 384 women at Australian fertility clinics, 62.5% achieved pregnancy, and among those who conceived, those with favorable cervical mucus symptoms reached pregnancy in a mean of 4.2 months.<sup><a href="#ref-8" id="cite-8a">8</a></sup> In Ukraine, Horodenchuk reported a mean time to pregnancy of 8 months.<sup><a href="#ref-7" id="cite-7b">7</a></sup> The Sanchez-Mendez study reported a median treatment duration of 10.9 months for the full cohort.<sup><a href="#ref-1" id="cite-1c">1</a></sup></p>

          <p>The Boyle JRRM study reported an average time to conception of 12 months for live birth patients, with most pregnancies occurring within the first year of treatment.<sup><a href="#ref-3" id="cite-3a">3</a></sup> This included patients with an average female age of 36.4 years and a mean of 32.2 months of prior infertility. These are not patients with simple problems who were always going to conceive quickly. They are patients with real diagnoses receiving targeted treatment.</p>

          <p>For context, a typical IVF journey involves two to three cycles spread over 9 to 18 months, including preparation, retrieval, transfer, and recovery between attempts. The time difference between RRM and IVF is measured in months, not years. And during those months of RRM treatment, you gain something that no IVF cycle provides: a comprehensive understanding of what was causing the problem in the first place. Even for patients who ultimately choose a different path, that diagnostic clarity has lasting value.</p>

          <!-- Section 4: Study Comparison Table -->
          <h2 id="study-table">Study Comparison Table</h2>

          <p>The table below summarizes all published RRM outcomes studies in one view. Each row represents a distinct cohort, ordered from the most recent publication to the earliest. Columns include patient demographics, study size, prior ART history, and the primary outcome measure with its reported rate. Because studies use different outcome definitions (conception, live birth, take-home baby) and follow-up periods, direct comparisons between rows require attention to those differences. Click any study name to read the full article in the RRM Academy Research Library.</p>

