          <!-- Section 5: How RRM Compares to IVF -->
          <h2 id="rrm-vs-ivf">How RRM Compares to IVF</h2>

          <p>RRM and IVF answer fundamentally different clinical questions. IVF bypasses the reproductive system to achieve fertilization in a laboratory. RRM investigates and treats the underlying causes of subfertility so that conception can happen naturally. Comparing the two requires understanding not just pregnancy rates, but the type of pregnancies produced, the risks involved, and the diagnostic information gained along the way.</p>

          <div class="table-responsive">
            <table>
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Measure</th>
                  <th>RRM</th>
                  <th>IVF</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Live birth rates</strong></td>
                  <td>32% to 66% cumulative over 24 months<sup><a href="#ref-9" id="cite-9d">9</a></sup><sup><a href="#ref-12" id="cite-12c">12</a></sup></td>
                  <td>~28% per cycle (SART); ~50% cumulative over 3 cycles</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Multiple pregnancy</strong></td>
                  <td>Near zero across all published cohorts</td>
                  <td>20 to 30% twin rate historically</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Preterm birth risk</strong></td>
                  <td>Comparable to general population</td>
                  <td>IVF: 4.24x higher; IUI: 3.17x higher<sup><a href="#ref-5" id="cite-5a">5</a></sup>. ART singleton preterm OR 3.28<sup><a href="#ref-11" id="cite-11a">11</a></sup></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Cost</strong></td>
                  <td>Diagnostic workup and treatment typically a fraction of IVF costs</td>
                  <td>$40,000 to $60,000 average (multiple cycles)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Diagnostic value</strong></td>
                  <td>Provides a specific diagnosis; reduces "unexplained" to under 10%<sup><a href="#ref-2" id="cite-2f">2</a></sup></td>
                  <td>Bypasses diagnosis; underlying cause often remains unknown</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>

          <p>These comparisons are not intended to suggest that one approach is universally superior. Patient circumstances vary widely, and some conditions are better served by one treatment path than another. The point is that the two approaches differ in what they measure, what they prioritize, and what they leave behind. RRM produces overwhelmingly singleton, full-term pregnancies. IVF carries well-documented elevations in preterm birth, low birth weight, and multiple gestations, even in singleton pregnancies conceived through ART.<sup><a href="#ref-5" id="cite-5b">5</a></sup><sup><a href="#ref-11" id="cite-11b">11</a></sup></p>

          <p>RRM and IVF are not mutually exclusive. Some patients begin with RRM to obtain a comprehensive diagnosis, then make informed decisions about next steps based on what was found. Others come to RRM after IVF has failed, as the de Groot/Boyle cohort demonstrates.<sup><a href="#ref-9" id="cite-9e">9</a></sup> The diagnostic information gained through an RRM workup belongs to the patient regardless of the treatment path ultimately chosen. Knowing the "why" behind infertility changes the conversation from "try again" to "here is what we can address."</p>

          <!-- Section 6: About the STORRM Registry -->
          <h2 id="storrm">About the STORRM Registry</h2>

          <p>STORRM (Surveillance of Treatment Outcomes for Restorative Reproductive Medicine) is an international research registry developed by the <a href="https://iirrm.org" rel="noopener" target="_blank">International Institute for Restorative Reproductive Medicine (IIRRM)</a> in collaboration with the University of Utah School of Medicine. Directed by Joseph Stanford, MD, STORRM was launched in 2023 at the IIRRM Congress in Lisbon, Portugal. The registry collects standardized outcomes data from RRM clinics worldwide, building the infrastructure needed for population-level evidence on RRM effectiveness.</p>

          <p>As STORRM enrollment grows, it will provide continuously updated, real-world outcomes data across diverse clinical settings, patient populations, and geographic regions. This represents a significant step beyond the single-center and multicenter studies summarized on this page. <a href="https://iirrm.org/STORRM" rel="noopener" target="_blank">Learn more about STORRM</a>.</p>

